---

<BaseLayout
  title="Free Even and Odd Worksheets - Printable Math Practice | ToolCalcs"
  description={ws.description}
  type="article"
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <nav class="breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo;
    <a href="/worksheets/">Worksheets</a> &rsaquo;
    <span>Even & Odd Worksheets</span>
  </nav>

  <h1>{ws.title}</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">{ws.description}</p>

  <div class="worksheet-box">
    <div class="config-panel">
      <h3>Settings</h3>
      <div class="config-inputs">
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgProblems">Number of Problems</label>
          <input type="number" id="cfgProblems" value="20" min="10" max="40" />
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgType">Problem Type</label>
          <select id="cfgType">
            <option value="classify">Classify (Even or Odd?)</option>
            <option value="color">Color Even Numbers</option>
            <option value="fill">Fill Missing Even/Odd</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgMaxNumber">Max Number</label>
          <select id="cfgMaxNumber">
            <option value="10">Up to 10</option>
            <option value="20" selected>Up to 20</option>
            <option value="50">Up to 50</option>
            <option value="100">Up to 100</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-actions">
      <button class="ws-btn primary" id="btnGenerate">Generate New</button>
      <button class="ws-btn print" id="btnPrint">Print</button>
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="toggleAnswers" />
        Show Answers
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-content" id="worksheetContent">
      <div class="worksheet-header-print">
        <h2>Even & Odd Numbers</h2>
        <div class="name-date">
          <span>Name: ___________________</span>
          <span>Date: ___________________</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div id="problemGrid"></div>
      <div class="answer-key hidden" id="answerKey">
        <h3>Answer Key</h3>
        <div class="answer-grid" id="answerGrid"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>What Are Even and Odd Numbers?</h2>
    <p>Even numbers are numbers that can be divided evenly by 2 with no remainder. They end in 0, 2, 4, 6, or 8. For example, 2, 14, 36, and 100 are all even numbers. Odd numbers are numbers that have a remainder of 1 when divided by 2. They end in 1, 3, 5, 7, or 9. For example, 1, 7, 23, and 99 are all odd numbers.</p>
    <p>Understanding even and odd numbers is a foundational number theory concept that appears throughout mathematics. It connects to skip counting by 2s, pairing objects, division, and later algebraic concepts. These free printable worksheets help students practice identifying, sorting, and working with even and odd numbers through three different activity types.</p>

    <h2>Grade-Level Guide</h2>
    <h3>Kindergarten (Ages 5-6)</h3>
    <p>Kindergartners begin to explore even and odd through hands-on activities. They pair objects and discover that some numbers make equal pairs while others have one left over. Use the "Up to 10" setting with the "Classify" type to introduce the concept. Keep problem counts small (10-12) and supplement with physical manipulatives.</p>

    <h3>First Grade (Ages 6-7)</h3>
    <p>First graders extend their understanding to numbers up to 20. They learn the pattern: even numbers end in 0, 2, 4, 6, or 8, and odd numbers end in 1, 3, 5, 7, or 9. The "Color Even Numbers" type provides a fun, visual activity where students find and highlight the even numbers in a grid. Use the "Up to 20" setting.</p>

    <h3>Second Grade (Ages 7-8)</h3>
    <p>Second graders master even and odd identification and begin exploring the properties of even and odd numbers in operations. They discover that even + even = even, odd + odd = even, and even + odd = odd. Use the "Up to 50" or "Up to 100" settings to challenge their pattern recognition with larger numbers. The "Fill Missing" type tests whether students can predict the next even or odd number in a sequence.</p>

    <h2>Three Types of Practice</h2>
    <h3>Classify (Even or Odd?)</h3>
    <p>Students look at each number and decide whether it is even or odd. This is the most direct way to practice the concept. Students should focus on the ones digit to determine the answer, especially for larger numbers. For example, 74 is even because the ones digit (4) is even, regardless of the tens digit.</p>

    <h3>Color Even Numbers</h3>
    <p>Students are given a grid of numbers and must identify and color (or circle) all the even numbers. This type creates a visual pattern that reinforces the concept. When students color the even numbers in a number chart, they can see the alternating pattern of even and odd numbers clearly.</p>

    <h3>Fill Missing Even/Odd</h3>
    <p>Students see a sequence of even or odd numbers with some blanks. They must fill in the missing numbers to complete the pattern. This type combines even/odd understanding with skip counting and pattern recognition skills. For example: 2, 4, ___, 8, 10, ___, 14.</p>

    <h2>Tips for Teaching Even and Odd</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use pairing.</strong> Give students a group of objects and have them try to make pairs. If every object has a partner, the number is even. If one is left over, the number is odd. This concrete experience makes the abstract concept tangible.</li>
      <li><strong>Teach the ones-digit shortcut.</strong> Once students understand the concept, teach them to look at only the last digit. This makes identifying even and odd numbers fast and automatic, even for very large numbers.</li>
      <li><strong>Connect to skip counting.</strong> Even numbers are what you say when counting by 2s: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, ... This connection reinforces both skills simultaneously.</li>
      <li><strong>Explore patterns.</strong> Write numbers 1-20 and have students color even numbers one color and odd numbers another. The alternating pattern is visually striking and helps cement understanding.</li>
      <li><strong>Discuss zero.</strong> Zero is even! It can be divided by 2 with no remainder (0 / 2 = 0), and it ends in 0. This is a common point of confusion worth addressing directly.</li>
      <li><strong>Use number charts.</strong> A hundred chart with even numbers highlighted reveals a beautiful pattern and shows students that exactly half of all counting numbers are even and half are odd.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to Use These Worksheets</h2>
    <p>Choose the number of problems, activity type, and maximum number using the settings above. Click "Generate New" for a fresh worksheet. "Classify" presents individual numbers to identify. "Color Even Numbers" presents a grid where students find even numbers. "Fill Missing" presents sequences with blanks. Use "Print" for clean output and "Show Answers" to check work.</p>

    <h2>Related Worksheets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/skip-counting/">Skip Counting Worksheets</a> - Count by 2s, 5s, 10s, and more.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/comparing-numbers-worksheets/">Comparing Numbers Worksheets</a> - Practice using &gt;, &lt;, and = symbols.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/place-value-worksheets/">Place Value Worksheets</a> - Understand digit values and number composition.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/number-tracing/">Number Tracing Worksheets</a> - Practice writing numbers 0-20.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-bottom" format="horizontal" />
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  var problems = [];
  var problemType = 'classify';

  function randInt(min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
  }

  function shuffle(arr) {
    for (var i = arr.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
      var j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
      var tmp = arr[i]; arr[i] = arr[j]; arr[j] = tmp;
    }
    return arr;
  }

  function generateProblems() {
    var count = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgProblems').value, 10);
    problemType = document.getElementById('cfgType').value;
    var maxNum = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgMaxNumber').value, 10);

    if (isNaN(count) || count < 10) count = 10;
    if (count > 40) count = 40;

    problems = [];

    if (problemType === 'classify') {
      var used = {};
      for (var i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        var n;
        do { n = randInt(0, maxNum); } while (used[n] && Object.keys(used).length < maxNum + 1);
        used[n] = true;
        problems.push({ number: n, answer: n % 2 === 0 ? 'Even' : 'Odd' });
      }
    } else if (problemType === 'color') {
      // Generate a grid of numbers; students mark the even ones
      var gridSize = Math.min(count, maxNum + 1);
      var all = [];
      for (var i = 0; i <= maxNum; i++) all.push(i);
      shuffle(all);
      for (var i = 0; i < gridSize; i++) {
        problems.push({ number: all[i], isEven: all[i] % 2 === 0 });
      }
      // Sort for nice grid display
      problems.sort(function (a, b) { return a.number - b.number; });
    } else {
      // Fill missing even/odd sequences
      var seqCount = Math.min(count, 20);
      for (var i = 0; i < seqCount; i++) {
        var isEvenSeq = Math.random() < 0.5;
        var start = isEvenSeq ? randInt(0, Math.floor(maxNum / 2)) * 2 : randInt(0, Math.floor(maxNum / 2)) * 2 + 1;
        var seq = [];
        for (var j = 0; j < 8; j++) {
          var val = start + j * 2;
          if (val > maxNum + 10) break;
          seq.push(val);
        }
        if (seq.length < 5) { i--; continue; }
        // Blank out 2-3 positions (not first or last)
        var blanks = [];
        var numBlanks = seq.length <= 5 ? 2 : 3;
        while (blanks.length < numBlanks) {
          var bi = randInt(1, seq.length - 2);
          if (blanks.indexOf(bi) === -1) blanks.push(bi);
        }
        problems.push({ sequence: seq, blanks: blanks, isEven: isEvenSeq });
      }
    }

    renderProblems();
    renderAnswerKey();
    updateAnswerVisibility();
  }

  function renderProblems() {
    var grid = document.getElementById('problemGrid');
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var html = '';

    if (problemType === 'classify') {
      html += '<div class="problem-grid">';
      for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
        var p = problems[i];
        html += '<div class="problem eo-classify">';
        html += '<div class="problem-number">' + (i + 1) + ')</div>';
        html += '<div class="eo-num">' + p.number + '</div>';
        html += '<div class="problem-answer' + (showAnswers ? ' revealed' : '') + '">';
        html += showAnswers ? p.answer : '___________';
        html += '</div>';
        html += '</div>';
      }
      html += '</div>';
    } else if (problemType === 'color') {
      html += '<p class="eo-instruction">Circle or color all the <strong>even</strong> numbers:</p>';
      html += '<div class="eo-grid">';
      for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
        var p = problems[i];
        var cls = 'eo-cell';
        if (showAnswers && p.isEven) cls += ' eo-even-highlight';
        html += '<div class="' + cls + '">' + p.number + '</div>';
      }
      html += '</div>';
    } else {
      html += '<p class="eo-instruction">Fill in the missing numbers in each sequence:</p>';
      for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
        var p = problems[i];
        html += '<div class="eo-seq-row">';
        html += '<span class="eo-seq-label">' + (i + 1) + ') ' + (p.isEven ? 'Even' : 'Odd') + ': </span>';
        for (var j = 0; j < p.sequence.length; j++) {
          var isBlank = p.blanks.indexOf(j) !== -1;
          if (isBlank && !showAnswers) {
            html += '<span class="eo-seq-blank">___</span>';
          } else if (isBlank && showAnswers) {
            html += '<span class="eo-seq-answer">' + p.sequence[j] + '</span>';
          } else {
            html += '<span class="eo-seq-num">' + p.sequence[j] + '</span>';
          }
          if (j < p.sequence.length - 1) html += '<span class="eo-seq-sep">,</span> ';
        }
        html += '</div>';
      }
    }

    grid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderAnswerKey() {
    var answerGrid = document.getElementById('answerGrid');
    var html = '';

    if (problemType === 'classify') {
      for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
        html += '<div class="answer-item">';
        html += '<span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span>';
        html += '<span class="a">' + problems[i].number + ' = ' + problems[i].answer + '</span>';
        html += '</div>';
      }
    } else if (problemType === 'color') {
      var evens = [];
      for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
        if (problems[i].isEven) evens.push(problems[i].number);
      }
      html += '<div class="answer-item"><span class="a">Even numbers: ' + evens.join(', ') + '</span></div>';
    } else {
      for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
        var p = problems[i];
        var blanked = [];
        for (var j = 0; j < p.blanks.length; j++) {
          blanked.push(p.sequence[p.blanks[j]]);
        }
        html += '<div class="answer-item">';
        html += '<span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span>';
        html += '<span class="a">' + blanked.join(', ') + '</span>';
        html += '</div>';
      }
    }

    answerGrid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function updateAnswerVisibility() {
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var answerKey = document.getElementById('answerKey');
    if (showAnswers) { answerKey.classList.remove('hidden'); }
    else { answerKey.classList.add('hidden'); }
    renderProblems();
  }

  document.getElementById('btnGenerate').addEventListener('click', generateProblems);
  document.getElementById('btnPrint').addEventListener('click', function () { window.print(); });
  document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').addEventListener('change', updateAnswerVisibility);
  generateProblems();
</script>

<style>
  :global(.eo-instruction) {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }
  :global(.eo-classify) {
    align-items: center !important;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  :global(.eo-num) {
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    min-width: 40px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  :global(.eo-grid) {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(52px, 1fr));
    gap: 8px;
    max-width: 600px;
  }
  :global(.eo-cell) {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    height: 48px;
    border: 2px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    background: #fff;
  }
  :global(.eo-even-highlight) {
    background: rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.12);
    border-color: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-primary);
  }
  :global(.eo-seq-row) {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 2px;
    padding: 8px 0;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  :global(.eo-seq-label) {
    font-weight: 600;
    min-width: 80px;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  :global(.eo-seq-num) {
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  :global(.eo-seq-blank) {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border);
    min-width: 36px;
    text-align: center;
    display: inline-block;
  }
  :global(.eo-seq-answer) {
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-primary);
    min-width: 36px;
    text-align: center;
    display: inline-block;
  }
  :global(.eo-seq-sep) {
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }
  @media print {
    :global(.eo-even-highlight) { background: none; border-color: #333; color: inherit; }
  }
</style>
